## ORM (Odoo 16 — pivot release between 12/13/14 and 17)

- Methods are **recordset by default**. `@api.multi` is **removed**; do not import or apply it.
- `@api.model` for class-level methods that don't need a recordset.
- `@api.model_create_multi` is **required** when overriding `create()`. A single-record `@api.model` `create()` override will silently break batch creates.
- `@api.depends`, `@api.constrains`, `@api.onchange`, `@api.depends_context` as in earlier versions.
- `name_get()` is still the standard display-name contract (`_compute_display_name` arrives in 17 — do not back-port it).
- Cache flush: prefer the new `recordset.flush_recordset([fnames])` / `self.env.flush_all()` API over ad-hoc `invalidate_cache` calls when an SQL statement must see in-memory writes.
- Call `ensure_one()` when a method assumes one record.
- Use parameterized SQL only. Batch `write()` and `unlink()` operations.
- Document every `sudo()` with a one-line reason in code.
- Prefer ORM over SQL. When SQL writes are unavoidable, `flush_recordset` first and invalidate or refresh affected caches after.

## Multi-company

- Set `_check_company_auto = True` on **any new model** that has company-scoped `Many2one` fields (i.e. fields whose comodel carries `company_id`). The ORM then validates cross-company references automatically — do not re-implement these checks by hand.
- Declare `check_company=True` on the company-scoped relational fields and add a `company_id` field with the standard default.

## Performance

- Avoid `search()` or `browse(id)` inside loops.
- Prefer `read_group(..., lazy=False)` for grouped counts and sums.
- Push filtering into domains; do not filter in Python after a broad search.
- Use `search_count()` instead of `len(search())`.
- Batch recordset work with `mapped`, `filtered`, grouped domains, and set operations.
- Keep computed fields prefetch-friendly; declare a complete `@api.depends`.
- Store computed fields only when they are searched, grouped, sorted, or repeatedly displayed at scale.

## Views and models

- Inheritance edits use `<xpath>` with `position="after|before|inside|replace|attributes"`.
- Keep XML IDs stable across releases.
- **New code**: write view conditions as Python expressions on the field — `invisible="…"`, `readonly="…"`, `required="…"`. This is the 17-ready form and is already supported in 16.
- **Legacy code**: `attrs="{...}"` and `states="…"` still parse in 16 (deprecated). Leave existing usages alone unless the task is an explicit migration; do not introduce new ones.
- Keep model methods small and focused. Use `_sql_constraints` or `@api.constrains` for validation.

## Frontend (OWL v2 by default)

- The web client is OWL v2 in 16; new components use the **class-based** syntax (`class Foo extends Component { setup() {…} }`), with `static template = "…"` and explicit `static props`.
- Templates use OWL XML with `t-*` directives.
- Legacy OWL v1 widgets and any remaining `Widget`-style components are migration targets, not patterns to copy.
- Do not introduce new jQuery selectors.

## Security and style

- Keep `ir.model.access.csv` and `ir.rule` aligned with new models.
- Raise `UserError` for business rules, `ValidationError` for invalid data.
- Use `_logger`, never `print()`.
- Imports order: stdlib, third-party, `odoo`, local — in that order.
- Respect multi-company and record rules unless the task explicitly requires privileged behaviour.

## Verification

- Module install/update: `{{PYTHON_BIN}} odoo-bin -u <module> --stop-after-init -d {{DEFAULT_DB}}` against the dev DB.
- Module tests: `--test-enable --test-tags /<module> --stop-after-init`.
- For algorithm correctness against real data, prefer `realdata_test.eval_orm_expression` and `consistency_check_eval` over UI-driven repro.
